 Lecture 6 Unimolecular Reactions and Collision Dynamics In the preceding chapters, we developed the steady-state approximation as a general tool for deriving rate laws from complex mechanisms. We now put it to work on real chemical problems. In this chapter, we tackle two puzzles that cannot be resolved without thinking carefully about elementary steps: how can a unimolecular reaction show pressure-dependent kinetics, and why do some apparently simple reactions require a third body to proceed? 6.1 The Lindemann–Hinshelwood Mechanism Many reactions that appear simple at first glance actually proceed through complex mechanisms involving multiple elementary steps. A classic example is the thermal decomposition of azomethane: \[\mathrm{CH_3N_2CH_3} ightarrow \mathrm{C_2H_6} + \mathrm{N_2}\] At high pressures, this reaction exhibits first-order kinetics: \[- rac{\mathrm{d}[\mathrm{CH_3N_2CH_3}]}{\mathrm{d}t} = k[\mathrm{CH_3N_2CH_3}]\] This simple rate law presents us with a fundamental mechanistic puzzle. We observe two seemingly contradictory behaviours: The reaction shows first-order kinetics (\(
u = k[\mathrm{A}]\)), suggesting each molecule reacts independently. The rate increases with temperature, indicating that energy is required to overcome an activation barrier. But how does each molecule acquire this activation energy? If the activation energy came from molecular collisions (the usual mechanism for thermal activation), we would expect the rate to depend on the frequency of these collisions. Since collision frequency is proportional to the concentration of both colliding species, this would lead to second-order kinetics (\(
u = k[\mathrm{A}]^2\)). Yet we observe first-order behaviour. Something more subtle must be going on. Figure 6.1: The unimolecular reaction paradox: the thermal decomposition of azomethane shows first-order kinetics at high pressure, yet the rate increases with temperature, implying collisional activation — which would suggest second-order kinetics. [Draft figure from lecture slides.] 6.1.1 The Mechanism In 1921, Frederick Lindemann proposed a three-step mechanism to resolve this paradox: Step 1 — Excitation by collision: \[\mathrm{A} + \mathrm{M} \xrightarrow{k_1} \mathrm{A^*} + \mathrm{M}\] Step 2 — Deactivation by collision: \[\mathrm{A^*} + \mathrm{M} \xrightarrow{k_{-1}} \mathrm{A} + \mathrm{M}\] Step 3 — Unimolecular decomposition: \[\mathrm{A^*} \xrightarrow{k_2} \mathrm{P}\] Here, M represents any collision partner (often the reactant molecule itself), and A* represents an energetically excited molecule that has acquired enough energy to react. The key insight is that activation (Step 1) and reaction (Step 3) are separate events. A molecule can be activated by one collision, then react at a later time — or it may lose its energy in another collision (Step 2) before it has a chance to react. Figure 6.2: The Lindemann mechanism: (1) A is excited by collision with M; (2) A* can be deactivated by a further collision; (3) A* decomposes unimolecularly to products. The SSA is applied to the reactive intermediate A*. [Draft figure from lecture slides.] 6.1.2 Applying the Steady-State Approximation The excited molecule A* is a reactive intermediate — it is formed by Step 1 and consumed by Steps 2 and 3. Applying the SSA: \[ rac{\mathrm{d}[\mathrm{A^*}]}{\mathrm{d}t} = k_1[\mathrm{A}][\mathrm{M}] - k_{-1}[\mathrm{A^*}][\mathrm{M}] - k_2[\mathrm{A^*}] \approx 0\] Solving for \([\mathrm{A^*}]\): \[[\mathrm{A^*}]_\mathrm{ss} =  rac{k_1[\mathrm{A}][\mathrm{M}]}{k_{-1}[\mathrm{M}] + k_2}\] The overall rate of product formation is then: \[ egin{equation} 
u = k_2[\mathrm{A^*}]_\mathrm{ss} =  rac{k_1 k_2[\mathrm{A}][\mathrm{M}]}{k_{-1}[\mathrm{M}] + k_2} 	ag{6.1} \end{equation}\] This is the Lindemann rate law. Notice that it has exactly the same mathematical structure as the SSA rate laws we derived in Lecture 5 (Eqn. (5.1)) — a ratio with competing terms in the denominator. The behaviour depends on which term dominates. For the specific case of azomethane decomposition, where the reactant itself acts as the collision partner (M = A): \[
u =  rac{k_1 k_2[\mathrm{A}]^2}{k_{-1}[\mathrm{A}] + k_2}\] 6.1.3 Pressure Dependence The denominator of Eqn. (6.1) contains \([\mathrm{M}]\), which is proportional to pressure. This gives the Lindemann mechanism a distinctive pressure dependence — the apparent reaction order changes with pressure. High-pressure limit (\(k_{-1}[\mathrm{M}] \gg k_2\)): At high pressures, collisions are frequent and deactivation is much faster than decomposition. The denominator is dominated by \(k_{-1}[\mathrm{M}]\): \[ egin{equation} 
u \approx  rac{k_1 k_2}{k_{-1}}[\mathrm{A}] 	ag{6.2} \end{equation}\] The reaction is first order in A, with an effective rate constant \(k_\mathrm{eff} = k_1 k_2/k_{-1}\). This explains the observed first-order kinetics at high pressures. Physically: excited molecules are produced and deactivated many times before any one of them happens to decompose. The rate-determining step is the unimolecular decomposition of A, and the concentration of A is maintained at its equilibrium value by the fast excitation–deactivation equilibrium. Low-pressure limit (\(k_{-1}[\mathrm{M}] \ll k_2\)): At low pressures, collisions are rare. Once a molecule is excited, it decomposes before it encounters another molecule that could deactivate it. The denominator is dominated by \(k_2\): \[ egin{equation} 
u \approx k_1[\mathrm{A}][\mathrm{M}] 	ag{6.3} \end{equation}\] The reaction is second order — first order in A and first order in M. The rate-determining step is now the excitation collision (Step 1), because every excited molecule goes on to react. This prediction was experimentally verified in 1927, providing strong support for the Lindemann mechanism. The Lindemann mechanism thus resolves the unimolecular paradox: the reaction is activated by collisions, but at high pressures the excitation–deactivation equilibrium is so fast that it is invisible to the experimenter. The observed kinetics reflect only the slow unimolecular decomposition step. Figure 6.3: The Lindemann rate law at high pressure: when collisional deactivation is much faster than unimolecular reaction (\(k_{-1}[\mathrm{M}] \gg k_2\)), the reaction is first order with effective rate constant \(k_1 k_2/k_{-1}\). [Draft figure from lecture slides.] You should be able to: Apply the SSA to the Lindemann mechanism to derive the rate law \(
u = k_1 k_2[\mathrm{A}][\mathrm{M}]/(k_{-1}[\mathrm{M}] + k_2)\), and predict the reaction order at high and low pressures by identifying which term dominates in the denominator. 6.2 Third-Order Reactions and Collision Dynamics 6.2.1 The NO Oxidation Puzzle Some reactions exhibit third-order kinetics, such as the oxidation of nitric oxide: \[2\mathrm{NO} + \mathrm{O_2} ightarrow 2\mathrm{NO_2}\] with rate law: \[
u = k[\mathrm{NO}]^2[\mathrm{O_2}]\] A termolecular collision mechanism — in which two NO molecules and one O2 molecule must collide simultaneously — seems implausible. Simultaneous three-body collisions are extremely rare events. Moreover, this reaction has the unusual property that its rate decreases with increasing temperature, suggesting a more complex mechanism. A pre-equilibrium mechanism provides a much better explanation: \[\mathrm{NO} + \mathrm{NO} \underset{k_{-1}}{\stackrel{k_1}{ightleftharpoons}} (\mathrm{NO})_2\] \[(\mathrm{NO})_2 + \mathrm{O_2} \xrightarrow{k_2} 2\mathrm{NO_2}\] At equilibrium: \[K =  rac{k_1}{k_{-1}} =  rac{[(\mathrm{NO})_2]}{[\mathrm{NO}]^2}\] The overall rate is: \[ egin{equation} 
u = k_2[(\mathrm{NO})_2][\mathrm{O_2}] = k_2 K[\mathrm{NO}]^2[\mathrm{O_2}] 	ag{6.4} \end{equation}\] This mechanism explains two key observations. First, the third-order kinetics: the rate depends on \([\mathrm{NO}]^2\) (from the equilibrium expression) and \([\mathrm{O_2}]\) (from the slow step), giving overall third-order behaviour without requiring a termolecular collision. Second, the negative temperature dependence: the dimerisation equilibrium in the first step is exothermic, so increasing the temperature shifts the equilibrium to the left (Le Chatelier’s principle), reducing \([(\mathrm{NO})_2]\) and hence slowing the overall reaction. The effective rate constant \(k_\mathrm{obs} = k_2 K\) decreases with temperature because \(K\) decreases faster than \(k_2\) increases. 6.2.2 Formation of Ozone: Why a Third Body is Needed Another important third-order reaction is ozone formation: \[\mathrm{O} + \mathrm{O_2} + \mathrm{M} ightarrow \mathrm{O_3} + \mathrm{M}\] with rate law: \[ egin{equation} 
u = k[\mathrm{O}][\mathrm{O_2}][\mathrm{M}] 	ag{6.5} \end{equation}\] where M represents a third body — any molecule present in the gas (typically N2 or O2). Why is a third body needed for this apparently simple combination reaction? The requirement arises from two fundamental constraints of molecular collisions: Energy conservation. The formation of ozone is highly exothermic, releasing approximately \(107\,\mathrm{kJ\,mol}^{-1}\) when the new O–O bond forms. A bimolecular collision between O and O2 produces a vibrationally excited ozone molecule, O3*, that contains all this excess energy in its vibrational modes. Momentum conservation. When O collides with O2, the total momentum of the system must be conserved. This constrains how the released energy is distributed: much of it ends up as internal vibrational energy of the O3* product rather than translational kinetic energy. The resulting O3* is so highly excited that it rapidly dissociates back to O + O2 — unless something removes the excess energy first. Figure 6.4: A bimolecular collision between O and O\(_2\) produces a vibrationally excited O\(_3^*\). Conservation of momentum and energy means the excess energy ends up as internal vibration, causing O\(_3^*\) to dissociate unless a third body M removes the energy. [Draft figure from lecture slides.] This is where the third body becomes essential. When the vibrationally excited O3* collides with M, the excess energy can be transferred to M as translational kinetic energy, allowing the ozone molecule to stabilise: Step 1 — Formation of excited ozone: \[\mathrm{O} + \mathrm{O_2} \underset{k_{-1}}{\stackrel{k_1}{ightleftharpoons}} \mathrm{O_3^*}\] Step 2 — Collisional stabilisation: \[\mathrm{O_3^*} + \mathrm{M} \xrightarrow{k_2} \mathrm{O_3} + \mathrm{M}\] Applying a pre-equilibrium approximation to O3* yields the observed third-order rate law (Eqn. (6.5)), with \(k_\mathrm{obs} = k_2 K = k_1 k_2/k_{-1}\). The necessity for a third body illustrates a general principle: highly exothermic reactions involving small molecules (with few internal degrees of freedom to absorb the energy) often cannot proceed as simple bimolecular encounters. A third-body collision provides the mechanism to remove excess energy, allowing the product to survive. This explains why third-order kinetics are common in atmospheric chemistry and combustion, where small radicals and atoms frequently combine. Appendix B explores why most other bimolecular reactions don’t require a third body, despite the same conservation laws applying to all collisions. You should be able to: Explain why a termolecular collision is implausible for the NO oxidation reaction, write a pre-equilibrium mechanism that reproduces the observed third-order rate law, and explain why ozone formation requires a third body. 6.3 Key Concepts The Lindemann–Hinshelwood mechanism resolves the unimolecular reaction paradox: activation occurs by collision (Step 1), but at high pressures the excitation–deactivation equilibrium is fast, making only the slow unimolecular decomposition visible. Applying the SSA to A* gives the Lindemann rate law, \(
u = k_1 k_2[\mathrm{A}][\mathrm{M}]/(k_{-1}[\mathrm{M}] + k_2)\), which predicts a transition from first-order to second-order kinetics as the pressure decreases. Third-order rate laws do not imply termolecular collisions. Pre-equilibrium mechanisms involving two sequential bimolecular steps can produce apparent third-order kinetics. The negative temperature dependence of the NO oxidation arises because the pre-equilibrium constant \(K\) decreases with temperature faster than \(k_2\) increases. Highly exothermic association reactions often require a third body to carry away excess energy from a vibrationally excited intermediate. Without this energy transfer, the product dissociates back to reactants. The SSA and pre-equilibrium approximation, developed in Lectures 4 and 5, are essential tools for understanding real reaction mechanisms — from gas-phase decomposition to atmospheric chemistry.

 Lecture 8 Chain Reactions So far, the mechanisms we have studied — consecutive reactions, pre-equilibria, enzyme catalysis — all lead to steady, predictable kinetics. But not all reactions behave so tamely. In a chain reaction, reactive intermediates are not merely consumed — they are regenerated by the very steps that form the products, creating a self-sustaining cycle. Understanding chain reactions requires the same SSA tools we have developed, but the results can be far more dramatic. 8.1 The H2 + Br2 Reaction The gas-phase reaction of hydrogen with bromine to form hydrogen bromide: \[\mathrm{H_2} + \mathrm{Br_2} ightarrow 2\mathrm{HBr}\] appears simple, but its experimentally determined rate law is anything but: \[ egin{equation} 
u =  rac{k[\mathrm{H_2}][\mathrm{Br_2}]^{1/2}}{1 + k&#39;[\mathrm{HBr}]/[\mathrm{Br_2}]} 	ag{8.1} \end{equation}\] This rate law has two unusual features: a fractional order of \( rac{1}{2}\) in Br2, and a term in the denominator that involves the product HBr. Neither feature can be explained by a single elementary step. To understand where this rate law comes from, we need to consider the full chain mechanism. 8.1.1 The Mechanism The reaction proceeds through a sequence of elementary steps involving two reactive intermediates — bromine radicals (\(\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet}\)) and hydrogen radicals (\(\mathrm{H}^{ ullet}\)): Initiation: \[\mathrm{Br_2} + \mathrm{M} \xrightarrow{k_1} 2\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{M}\] Propagation: \[ egin{align*} \mathrm{Br}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{H_2} &amp;\xrightarrow{k_2} \mathrm{H}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{HBr} \ \mathrm{H}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{Br_2} &amp;\xrightarrow{k_3} \mathrm{Br}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{HBr} \end{align*}\] Inhibition (reverse of first propagation step): \[\mathrm{H}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{HBr} \xrightarrow{k_{-2}} \mathrm{Br}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{H_2}\] Termination: \[2\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{M} \xrightarrow{k_4} \mathrm{Br_2} + \mathrm{M}\] Figure 8.1: The cyclic nature of the H\(_2\) + Br\(_2\) chain reaction. Bromine radicals are consumed in one propagation step and regenerated in the next, creating a self-sustaining cycle that produces two molecules of HBr per turn. The inhibition step diverts H\(^ ullet\) back to Br\(^ ullet\) without forming product. [Draft figure from lecture slides.] Notice the cyclic structure of the propagation steps: \(\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet}\) is consumed in the first propagation step and regenerated in the second. Each complete cycle of propagation produces two molecules of HBr and regenerates the radical that started the cycle. This is the defining feature of a chain reaction — the intermediates catalyse their own regeneration. 8.1.2 Deriving the Rate Law Using the SSA We apply the SSA to both radical intermediates. The key simplification comes from a physical observation: the propagation steps are much faster than initiation and termination. This means that in the SSA equation for \(\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet}\), the propagation terms nearly cancel (each \(\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet}\) consumed in one propagation step is regenerated in the next). What remains is a balance between initiation and termination: \[2k_1[\mathrm{Br_2}][\mathrm{M}] = 2k_4[\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet}]^2[\mathrm{M}]\] \[ egin{equation} [\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet}]_\mathrm{ss} = \sqrt{ rac{k_1}{k_4}}\,[\mathrm{Br_2}]^{1/2} 	ag{8.2} \end{equation}\] This result immediately explains the \([\mathrm{Br_2}]^{1/2}\) dependence in the experimental rate law: it comes from the square root in the steady-state radical concentration, which in turn arises because termination is second order in \(\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet}\) (two radicals must meet to recombine). Applying the SSA to \(\mathrm{H}^{ ullet}\) and substituting \([\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet}]_\mathrm{ss}\), we can derive the full rate of HBr formation. The algebra is involved (and the details are not examinable), but the result is: \[ egin{equation} 
u =  rac{2k_2\sqrt{k_1/k_4}\,[\mathrm{H_2}][\mathrm{Br_2}]^{1/2}}{1 + (k_{-2}/k_3)[\mathrm{HBr}]/[\mathrm{Br_2}]} 	ag{8.3} \end{equation}\] This matches the experimental rate law (Eqn. (8.1)) exactly, with \(k = 2k_2\sqrt{k_1/k_4}\) and \(k&#39; = k_{-2}/k_3\). 8.1.3 Physical Interpretation The derived rate law tells us two things about the mechanism: The \([\mathrm{Br_2}]^{1/2}\) dependence arises because the steady-state radical concentration depends on the square root of the Br2 concentration (Eqn. (8.2)). This is a direct consequence of the bimolecular termination step. The inhibition by HBr appears in the denominator. The inhibition step (\(\mathrm{H}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{HBr} ightarrow \mathrm{Br}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{H_2}\)) competes with the forward propagation step (\(\mathrm{H}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{Br_2} ightarrow \mathrm{Br}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{HBr}\)). Both consume \(\mathrm{H}^{ ullet}\), but only the forward step produces HBr. The ratio \([\mathrm{HBr}]/[\mathrm{Br_2}]\) in the denominator captures this competition: as product accumulates relative to reactant, inhibition becomes increasingly important and the reaction slows down. This is an example of a negative reaction order — a phenomenon explored further in Appendix C. You should be able to: Identify the initiation, propagation, termination, and inhibition steps in the H2 + Br2 mechanism, explain the physical origin of the \([\mathrm{Br_2}]^{1/2}\) dependence and the inhibition term, and describe how the SSA is applied to derive the rate law. 8.2 The Anatomy of a Chain Reaction The H2 + Br2 reaction illustrates the general features shared by all chain reactions: Initiation — A step that creates reactive intermediates (usually radicals) from stable molecules. This is often slow and may require an external energy source (heat, light, or a chemical initiator). Propagation — A cyclic sequence of steps in which each step consumes one reactive intermediate and generates another. The cycle produces product molecules while regenerating the intermediates that sustain the chain. Termination — Steps that remove reactive intermediates from the cycle, usually by radical recombination. These steps compete with propagation and ultimately limit the chain length. Inhibition — Steps that consume intermediates unproductively (regenerating reactants rather than forming products). Not all chain reactions have inhibition steps, but when present they reduce the overall rate. Figure 8.2: The general anatomy of a chain reaction: initiation creates reactive intermediates (R\(_1\), R\(_2\)), propagation regenerates them in a cyclic sequence while producing products (P), and termination removes them. The competition between propagation and termination determines whether the chain is sustained. [Draft figure from lecture slides.] 8.2.1 Straight Chains versus Branching Chains Chain reactions fall into two fundamentally different categories, depending on what happens to the number of reactive intermediates during propagation. In a straight chain reaction, each propagation step regenerates exactly one reactive intermediate for every one consumed. The H2 + Br2 reaction is an example: when \(\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet}\) reacts, it produces one \(\mathrm{H}^{ ullet}\); when \(\mathrm{H}^{ ullet}\) reacts, it produces one \(\mathrm{Br}^{ ullet}\). The total number of radicals is maintained by the propagation cycle and slowly depleted by termination. Straight chain reactions reach a steady state. In a branching chain reaction, one or more propagation steps produce more reactive intermediates than they consume. The combustion of hydrogen provides the classic example: \[ egin{align*} \mathrm{H}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{O_2} &amp;ightarrow \mathrm{OH}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{O}^{ ullet ullet} \ \mathrm{O}^{ ullet ullet} + \mathrm{H_2} &amp;ightarrow \mathrm{OH}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{H}^{ ullet} \ \mathrm{OH}^{ ullet} + \mathrm{H_2} &amp;ightarrow \mathrm{H_2O} + \mathrm{H}^{ ullet} \end{align*}\] In the first step, one radical (\(\mathrm{H}^{ ullet}\)) generates two new radicals (\(\mathrm{OH}^{ ullet}\) and \(\mathrm{O}^{ ullet ullet}\)). This means the radical population can grow with each cycle. If this branching outpaces termination, the radical concentration increases exponentially — and the reaction accelerates towards an explosion. Whether a chain reaction reaches a steady state or runs away to explosion depends on the competition between branching (which multiplies intermediates) and termination (which removes them). In the next chapter, we develop this idea quantitatively using a general feedback model. You should be able to: Classify the steps in a chain reaction mechanism as initiation, propagation, termination, or inhibition, and distinguish between straight chain and branching chain reactions based on whether propagation steps conserve or multiply the number of reactive intermediates. 8.3 Key Concepts Chain reactions involve a cyclic propagation sequence in which reactive intermediates (usually radicals) are regenerated by the steps that produce the products. The H2 + Br2 rate law, \(
u = k[\mathrm{H_2}][\mathrm{Br_2}]^{1/2}/(1 + k&#39;[\mathrm{HBr}]/[\mathrm{Br_2}])\), is derived by applying the SSA to both radical intermediates. The \([\mathrm{Br_2}]^{1/2}\) dependence arises from bimolecular termination; the HBr inhibition term arises from a reverse propagation step. Every chain reaction has initiation (creating intermediates), propagation (regenerating them while forming products), and termination (removing them). Some also have inhibition steps. In a straight chain, each propagation cycle conserves the number of intermediates. In a branching chain, propagation multiplies the number of intermediates, potentially leading to exponential growth and explosion. The competition between branching and termination determines whether a chain reaction reaches a steady state or runs away — a question we analyse quantitatively in the next chapter.

 Lecture 9 Feedback, Stability, and Explosions In the previous chapter, we saw that chain reactions can be classified as straight or branching depending on whether propagation conserves or multiplies the number of reactive intermediates. We now ask the quantitative question: what determines whether a chain reaction reaches a steady state or explodes? The answer lies in a simple differential equation whose behaviour is controlled by a single parameter — the feedback parameter \(\phi\). 9.1 The General Feedback Equation Consider a reactive intermediate I that is produced by initiation and whose concentration changes through two competing effects: Initiation creates new intermediates at a constant rate \(
u_f = k_\mathrm{init}[\mathrm{M}]\), independent of \([\mathrm{I}]\). Propagation and termination together cause \([\mathrm{I}]\) to grow or decay at a rate proportional to \([\mathrm{I}]\) itself. The rate equation for I is: \[ egin{equation}  rac{\mathrm{d}[\mathrm{I}]}{\mathrm{d}t} = 
u_f + \phi[\mathrm{I}] 	ag{9.1} \end{equation}\] where \(\phi\) is the feedback parameter that captures the net effect of all processes that depend on the intermediate concentration. The sign of \(\phi\) determines everything. 9.1.1 What Determines \(\phi\)? The feedback parameter \(\phi\) reflects the competition between processes that create intermediates and processes that remove them: For a straight chain reaction (e.g. H2 + Br2), the propagation steps conserve the number of intermediates — every radical consumed produces exactly one new radical. The net effect on \([\mathrm{I}]\) comes only from termination, which removes intermediates: \[\phi = -k_\mathrm{term}\] Since \(k_\mathrm{term} &gt; 0\), the feedback parameter is negative. Termination acts as a brake: the faster the intermediates build up, the faster they are removed by recombination. For a branching chain reaction (e.g. H2/O2 combustion), the propagation steps multiply intermediates. Each propagation cycle creates new radicals at a rate proportional to \([\mathrm{I}]\), competing with termination: \[\phi = k_\mathrm{branch} - k_\mathrm{term}\] Now the sign of \(\phi\) depends on which process wins. If termination dominates (\(k_\mathrm{term} &gt; k_\mathrm{branch}\)), then \(\phi &lt; 0\) and the system behaves like a straight chain — it reaches a steady state. If branching dominates (\(k_\mathrm{branch} &gt; k_\mathrm{term}\)), then \(\phi &gt; 0\) and the intermediate concentration grows without bound. Figure 9.1: A branching chain reaction: each propagation step produces two intermediates from one, leading to exponential growth in the radical population. If branching outpaces termination (\(\phi &gt; 0\)), the number of intermediates doubles with each cycle. [Draft figure from lecture slides.] 9.2 Solving the Feedback Equation Eqn. (9.1) is a first-order linear ODE that we can solve by separation of variables. With the initial condition \([\mathrm{I}]_0 = 0\): \[ rac{\mathrm{d}[\mathrm{I}]}{
u_f + \phi[\mathrm{I}]} = \mathrm{d}t\] Integrating both sides: \[ rac{1}{\phi}\ln\left( rac{
u_f + \phi[\mathrm{I}]_t}{
u_f}ight) = t\] Rearranging: \[ egin{equation} [\mathrm{I}]_t =  rac{
u_f}{\phi}\left(\mathrm{e}^{\phi t} - 1ight) 	ag{9.2} \end{equation}\] This single equation describes both stable and explosive behaviour, depending entirely on the sign of \(\phi\). 9.2.1 Negative Feedback (\(\phi &lt; 0\)): Steady State When \(\phi &lt; 0\), the exponential term \(\mathrm{e}^{\phi t}\) decays to zero as \(t ightarrow \infty\). The intermediate concentration approaches a constant value: \[[\mathrm{I}]_\infty =  rac{
u_f}{|\phi|}\] This is a steady state: the rate of initiation is exactly balanced by the rate of termination. The system is self-regulating — if \([\mathrm{I}]\) rises above the steady-state value, the increased termination rate pulls it back down. This is the scenario that underpins the steady-state approximation we have used throughout the course. The time to reach the steady state is characterised by \(	au = 1/|\phi|\). If \(|\phi|\) is large (fast termination), the steady state is reached quickly and persists for most of the reaction — exactly the conditions under which the SSA is valid. 9.2.2 Positive Feedback (\(\phi &gt; 0\)): Explosion When \(\phi &gt; 0\), the exponential term \(\mathrm{e}^{\phi t}\) grows without bound. The intermediate concentration increases exponentially: \[[\mathrm{I}]_t \approx  rac{
u_f}{\phi}\,\mathrm{e}^{\phi t} \qquad 	ext{(for large } t	ext{)}\] Branching creates intermediates faster than termination can remove them. Each new radical generates more than one replacement, leading to a cascade. The radical population — and hence the reaction rate — increases exponentially. This is a chain-branching explosion: the reaction accelerates catastrophically until limited by reactant depletion or physical containment. Figure 9.2: Solutions to the feedback equation for negative and positive feedback. When \(\phi &lt; 0\), \([\mathrm{I}]\) rises to a steady state \(
u_f/|\phi|\) (lower curve). When \(\phi &gt; 0\), \([\mathrm{I}]\) grows exponentially — the signature of a chain-branching explosion (upper curve). [Draft figure from lecture slides.] You should be able to: Write the general feedback equation \(\mathrm{d}[\mathrm{I}]/\mathrm{d}t = 
u_f + \phi[\mathrm{I}]\), explain the physical meaning of the feedback parameter \(\phi\), and predict whether a chain reaction will reach a steady state (\(\phi &lt; 0\)) or explode (\(\phi &gt; 0\)) from the relative rates of branching and termination. 9.3 From Mechanism to Stability We can now connect the abstract feedback parameter \(\phi\) to the elementary steps of a specific mechanism. Consider a general chain reaction with initiation, propagation, branching, and termination: Initiation: \(\mathrm{M} \xrightarrow{k_\mathrm{init}} \mathrm{I}\) (rate \(= k_\mathrm{init}[\mathrm{M}] = 
u_f\)) Propagation (straight): \(\mathrm{I} + \mathrm{A} \xrightarrow{k_\mathrm{prop}} \mathrm{I} + 	ext{products}\) (no net change in [I]) Branching: \(\mathrm{I} + \mathrm{A} \xrightarrow{k_\mathrm{branch}} 2\mathrm{I} + 	ext{products}\) (net gain of one I) Termination: \(\mathrm{I} \xrightarrow{k_\mathrm{term}} 	ext{inactive products}\) (net loss of one I) The rate equation for I is: \[ rac{\mathrm{d}[\mathrm{I}]}{\mathrm{d}t} = \underbrace{
u_f}_{	ext{initiation}} + \underbrace{k_\mathrm{branch}[\mathrm{A}]}_{	ext{branching}} \cdot [\mathrm{I}] - \underbrace{k_\mathrm{term}}_{	ext{termination}} \cdot [\mathrm{I}]\] This has the form of Eqn. (9.1) with: \[ egin{equation} \phi = k_\mathrm{branch}[\mathrm{A}] - k_\mathrm{term} 	ag{9.3} \end{equation}\] This expression reveals why conditions matter: Concentration dependence. If the branching step involves a reactant A, then \(\phi\) depends on \([\mathrm{A}]\). A dilute mixture may have \(\phi &lt; 0\) (safe), while a concentrated mixture has \(\phi &gt; 0\) (explosive). This is why fuel–air mixtures explode only above a certain concentration. Pressure dependence. In gas-phase reactions, termination often occurs at surfaces (vessel walls), while branching occurs in the gas phase. Changing the pressure alters the balance: at low pressure, molecules reach the walls easily and \(k_\mathrm{term}\) is large (safe); at intermediate pressures, gas-phase branching may dominate (explosive); at very high pressures, three-body termination in the gas phase becomes important and the system may become safe again. Temperature dependence. The rate constants \(k_\mathrm{branch}\) and \(k_\mathrm{term}\) have different activation energies. Raising the temperature may push \(\phi\) from negative to positive, triggering an explosion. These considerations explain why hydrogen–oxygen mixtures have complex explosion limits — boundaries in pressure–temperature space that separate explosive from non-explosive conditions. The limits correspond to the condition \(\phi = 0\), where branching and termination are exactly balanced. You should be able to: Given a chain reaction mechanism with initiation, branching, and termination steps, write the feedback equation for the reactive intermediate, identify the feedback parameter \(\phi\), and predict the conditions (concentration, pressure, temperature) under which the reaction will reach a steady state or become explosive. 9.4 Key Concepts The feedback equation \(\mathrm{d}[\mathrm{I}]/\mathrm{d}t = 
u_f + \phi[\mathrm{I}]\) describes the evolution of reactive intermediates in chain reactions. The initiation rate \(
u_f\) creates intermediates; the feedback parameter \(\phi\) determines whether they accumulate or are controlled. For straight chains, \(\phi = -k_\mathrm{term} &lt; 0\): termination provides negative feedback and the system reaches a steady state. For branching chains, \(\phi = k_\mathrm{branch}[\mathrm{A}] - k_\mathrm{term}\): the sign depends on the competition between branching (which multiplies intermediates) and termination (which removes them). The general solution \([\mathrm{I}]_t = (
u_f/\phi)(\mathrm{e}^{\phi t} - 1)\) describes both steady-state behaviour (\(\phi &lt; 0\)) and explosive runaway (\(\phi &gt; 0\)) within a single equation. Explosion limits correspond to the condition \(\phi = 0\). They depend on concentration, pressure, and temperature because these variables affect the rates of branching and termination differently. The SSA is valid precisely when \(\phi &lt; 0\) and \(|\phi|\) is large — the intermediate reaches its steady state quickly and stays there. Positive feedback (\(\phi &gt; 0\)) represents the breakdown of the SSA.
